      "fontSize": 28,
      "fontFamily": 1,
      "text": "High Level Design\n\nThe system has one new component: the Chat Orchestrator Service. It sits between the client and everything else — the LLM, the existing Evidence\nRules API, the Session DB, encrypted object storage for files, and the external Case Service. The orchestrator is the source of truth and\ngatekeeper; the LLM is only the conversational front-end.\n\nSession Lifecycle and Resume\nWhen the user opens the app, the client calls GET /sessions/active with the transaction_id (user_id comes from the auth token, never the request\nbody). If an active or paused session exists for that (user_id, transaction_id) pair, the UI resumes it: the checklist progress is shown and the chat\ncontinues with a short recap built by templating (invoice: collected, proof of delivery: pending) rather than replaying the whole transcript into the LLM\ncontext. If no session exists, POST /sessions creates one: the orchestrator resolves the payment purpose, calls the Evidence Rules API to get the\nrequired evidence list, and persists it as evidence_requirements rows.\n\nA unique constraint on (user_id, transaction_id) for active/paused sessions guarantees there is never more than one resumable session per payment,\nso resume is never ambiguous. Every state change and every collected evidence item is persisted immediately, not batched — a crash or pause loses\nnothing, and resume works from any device.\n\nThe Core Loop: LLM Proposes, Orchestrator Decides\nThis is the most important design rule. The LLM never directly causes a state change — it cannot mark evidence as collected, advance the\nchecklist, or create a case. On every user turn:\n\n- The orchestrator sends the user message to the LLM with two jobs in one call: produce a natural-language reply, and emit a structured\nextraction proposal (tool call) checked against ALL pending requirement schemas, not just the one currently being asked.\n- The orchestrator validates each proposal deterministically: does the value match the requirement's real schema (enum values, email/phone format,\netc.), and is that requirement still pending?\n- Only if validation passes does the orchestrator write the evidence_items row, flip the requirement to collected, and log the acceptance. It then\ntells the LLM what happened, and the LLM acknowledges it to the user in plain language.\n\nExample: the requirement is refund_reason (enum: DAMAGED_ITEM, WRONG_ITEM, NOT_DELIVERED, OTHER). User says \"it never showed up, it's\nbeen three weeks\". The LLM proposes {reason: NOT_DELIVERED, description: \"...\"}. The orchestrator checks the enum is valid and the requirement is\npending, then accepts. If the extraction were ambiguous, the item stays pending and the bot re-asks — the LLM never decides \"close enough\".\n\nOut-of-Order Answers\nBecause extraction runs against all pending schemas every turn, over-answering and out-of-order answers work naturally. If the bot asks for an\nemail and the user gives a phone number that is a later requirement, the orchestrator accepts it against the phone_number requirement, leaves email\npending, and the LLM says \"Got your phone number, thanks — I'll still need your email\". Data matching no pending requirement is never silently dropped:\nthe bot clarifies, or stores it as an unstructured note for review. Every requirement declares a validator; every message is checked against all open\nvalidators.\n\n",
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "High Level Design\n\nThe system has one new component: the Chat Orchestrator Service. It sits between the client and everything else — the LLM, the existing Evidence Rules API, the Session DB, encrypted object storage for files, and the external Case Service. The orchestrator is the source of truth and gatekeeper; the LLM is only the conversational front-end.\n\nSession Lifecycle and Resume\nWhen the user opens the app, the client calls GET /sessions/active with the transaction_id (user_id comes from the auth token, never the request body). If an active or paused session exists for that (user_id, transaction_id) pair, the UI resumes it: the checklist progress is shown and the chat continues with a short recap built by templating (invoice: collected, proof of delivery: pending) rather than replaying the whole transcript into the LLM context. If no session exists, POST /sessions creates one: the orchestrator resolves the payment purpose, calls the Evidence Rules API to get the required evidence list, and persists it as evidence_requirements rows.\n\nA unique constraint on (user_id, transaction_id) for active/paused sessions guarantees there is never more than one resumable session per payment, so resume is never ambiguous. Every state change and every collected evidence item is persisted immediately, not batched — a crash or pause loses nothing, and resume works from any device.\n\nThe Core Loop: LLM Proposes, Orchestrator Decides\nThis is the most important design rule. The LLM never directly causes a state change — it cannot mark evidence as collected, advance the checklist, or create a case. On every user turn:\n\n- The orchestrator sends the user message to the LLM with two jobs in one call: produce a natural-language reply, and emit a structured extraction proposal (tool call) checked against ALL pending requirement schemas, not just the one currently being asked.\n- The orchestrator validates each proposal deterministically: does the value match the requirement's real schema (enum values, email/phone format, etc.), and is that requirement still pending?\n- Only if validation passes does the orchestrator write the evidence_items row, flip the requirement to collected, and log the acceptance. It then tells the LLM what happened, and the LLM acknowledges it to the user in plain language.\n\nExample: the requirement is refund_reason (enum: DAMAGED_ITEM, WRONG_ITEM, NOT_DELIVERED, OTHER). User says \"it never showed up, it's been three weeks\". The LLM proposes {reason: NOT_DELIVERED, description: \"...\"}. The orchestrator checks the enum is valid and the requirement is pending, then accepts. If the extraction were ambiguous, the item stays pending and the bot re-asks — the LLM never decides \"close enough\".\n\nOut-of-Order Answers\nBecause extraction runs against all pending schemas every turn, over-answering and out-of-order answers work naturally. If the bot asks for an email and the user gives a phone number that is a later requirement, the orchestrator accepts it against the phone_number requirement, leaves email pending, and the LLM says \"Got your phone number, thanks — I'll still need your email\". Data matching no pending requirement is never silently dropped: the bot clarifies, or stores it as an unstructured note for review. Every requirement declares a validator; every message is checked against all open validators.\n\n",
