      "text": "File Evidence and LLM-as-Judge\nFiles are uploaded to encrypted object storage; the DB holds only storage_ref pointers. Deterministic validation (file type, size, virus scan) is owned by the\norchestrator. For fuzzy checks — does this document plausibly look like an invoice for this amount/date — an LLM-as-judge is used, with strict rules: a\nseparate minimal prompt that never sees the conversational system prompt, a narrow output schema (verdict pass/fail/uncertain + confidence + reason), and\nits verdict is a routing signal, not a decision — low confidence routes to human review rather than auto-reject. Every judge input/output pair is logged.\n\nPrompt Injection Defense\nThe threat is the user, or hidden text inside an uploaded file, instructing the LLM to skip requirements or fake collection. Defenses, in order of importance:\n- The LLM cannot cause state changes, so a hijacked response has no payoff — it cannot forge evidence or create a case.\n- Extracted file text is wrapped as tagged data (document_content tags) and the model is instructed that tag contents are data, never instructions. The\njudge prompt has the same rule.\n- Structured output that does not parse against the expected schema is discarded, never interpreted charitably.\n- The LLM only has tools scoped to this session and transaction — no general API access — and the system prompt contains no secrets worth leaking.\n\nPrompt Architecture\nNo single god prompt. One prompt trying to do tone + extraction + judging degrades extraction reliability and is a bigger injection surface. Instead: a\nconversational prompt (explain, ask, acknowledge — sees checklist state, not rules logic), an extraction prompt (strict JSON proposals against all pending\nschemas), and an isolated judge prompt. Conversational + extraction share one API call per turn (Claude emits text and a tool call together) to save latency;\nthe judge stays a genuinely separate call because isolation is its whole point. Resume recaps use plain templating, no LLM needed.\n\nCase Creation and Failure Handling\nWhen all requirements are collected or waived, the session moves to READY_FOR_CASE and the orchestrator calls the Case Service: POST /cases, then\nattaches each evidence item. Case creation is idempotent on (transaction_id, session_id), so retries never create duplicate cases. If the Case Service is down,\nthe session simply stays in READY_FOR_CASE and retries with backoff — the evidence is already durably stored, only the linking step needs retrying. If the\nRules API is down at session start, the session holds in a retry state; the LLM never guesses what evidence is required, since the rules must stay centralized\nand auditable. Rejected evidence flips the requirement back to pending and the bot re-asks. Abandoned sessions expire via TTL and a cleanup job.\n\nEvaluation and Monitoring\nTwo different uses of a judge model, not to be conflated:\n\n- Inline judge (hot path, 100% of fuzzy cases): validates evidence content that schema checks cannot cover — e.g. does this uploaded PDF plausibly look like\nan invoice for this payment. Runs on every file evidence submission. Its verdict is a routing signal: pass accepts, uncertain/fail routes to human review or re-\nask. It gates state changes.\n\n- Offline evaluation (sampled, out of the request path): sample a percentage of conversations (e.g. 1-5%) and have a judge score them after the fact —\nextraction accuracy, whether the bot stayed on-topic, whether requirements were asked correctly, tone. Results feed a dashboard to track quality drift over\ntime (prompt regressions, model version changes). This never affects a live session.\n\nAlongside sampled evaluation, track deterministic metrics that need no LLM: extraction acceptance rate (how often proposals pass schema validation), re-ask\nrate per requirement, sessions completed vs abandoned, time-to-case-creation, and judge uncertain/fail rates. A sudden shift in any of these is the earliest\nsignal that a prompt or model change degraded quality.\n\n",
      "fontSize": 28,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "File Evidence and LLM-as-Judge\nFiles are uploaded to encrypted object storage; the DB holds only storage_ref pointers. Deterministic validation (file type, size, virus scan) is owned by the orchestrator. For fuzzy checks — does this document plausibly look like an invoice for this amount/date — an LLM-as-judge is used, with strict rules: a separate minimal prompt that never sees the conversational system prompt, a narrow output schema (verdict pass/fail/uncertain + confidence + reason), and its verdict is a routing signal, not a decision — low confidence routes to human review rather than auto-reject. Every judge input/output pair is logged.\n\nPrompt Injection Defense\nThe threat is the user, or hidden text inside an uploaded file, instructing the LLM to skip requirements or fake collection. Defenses, in order of importance:\n- The LLM cannot cause state changes, so a hijacked response has no payoff — it cannot forge evidence or create a case.\n- Extracted file text is wrapped as tagged data (document_content tags) and the model is instructed that tag contents are data, never instructions. The judge prompt has the same rule.\n- Structured output that does not parse against the expected schema is discarded, never interpreted charitably.\n- The LLM only has tools scoped to this session and transaction — no general API access — and the system prompt contains no secrets worth leaking.\n\nPrompt Architecture\nNo single god prompt. One prompt trying to do tone + extraction + judging degrades extraction reliability and is a bigger injection surface. Instead: a conversational prompt (explain, ask, acknowledge — sees checklist state, not rules logic), an extraction prompt (strict JSON proposals against all pending schemas), and an isolated judge prompt. Conversational + extraction share one API call per turn (Claude emits text and a tool call together) to save latency; the judge stays a genuinely separate call because isolation is its whole point. Resume recaps use plain templating, no LLM needed.\n\nCase Creation and Failure Handling\nWhen all requirements are collected or waived, the session moves to READY_FOR_CASE and the orchestrator calls the Case Service: POST /cases, then attaches each evidence item. Case creation is idempotent on (transaction_id, session_id), so retries never create duplicate cases. If the Case Service is down, the session simply stays in READY_FOR_CASE and retries with backoff — the evidence is already durably stored, only the linking step needs retrying. If the Rules API is down at session start, the session holds in a retry state; the LLM never guesses what evidence is required, since the rules must stay centralized and auditable. Rejected evidence flips the requirement back to pending and the bot re-asks. Abandoned sessions expire via TTL and a cleanup job.\n\nEvaluation and Monitoring\nTwo different uses of a judge model, not to be conflated:\n\n- Inline judge (hot path, 100% of fuzzy cases): validates evidence content that schema checks cannot cover — e.g. does this uploaded PDF plausibly look like an invoice for this payment. Runs on every file evidence submission. Its verdict is a routing signal: pass accepts, uncertain/fail routes to human review or re-ask. It gates state changes.\n\n- Offline evaluation (sampled, out of the request path): sample a percentage of conversations (e.g. 1-5%) and have a judge score them after the fact — extraction accuracy, whether the bot stayed on-topic, whether requirements were asked correctly, tone. Results feed a dashboard to track quality drift over time (prompt regressions, model version changes). This never affects a live session.\n\nAlongside sampled evaluation, track deterministic metrics that need no LLM: extraction acceptance rate (how often proposals pass schema validation), re-ask rate per requirement, sessions completed vs abandoned, time-to-case-creation, and judge uncertain/fail rates. A sudden shift in any of these is the earliest signal that a prompt or model change degraded quality.\n\n",
