      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "Model and Prompt Versioning, A/B Testing\nPrompts and model choice are config, not code. A prompt registry holds prompt_id, version, template, and model_id. Every session\nrecords which prompt versions and model it ran with, so any quality shift can be attributed.\n\nVariant assignment happens at session start: deterministic hash of user_id into a bucket, variant stamped on the session row.\nNever switch model or prompt mid-session — assignment is sticky for the whole conversation.\n\nComparison uses the metrics already defined in Evaluation and Monitoring, split per variant: extraction acceptance rate (proposals\npassing schema validation), re-ask rate per requirement, session completion vs abandonment, time-to-case-creation, plus sampled\noffline-judge quality scores. Guardrail metrics protect against misleading wins — e.g. a variant with higher completion but double the\nschema-rejection rate is not an improvement.\n\nBecause the LLM only proposes and the orchestrator decides, candidates can run in shadow mode on real traffic with zero user\nimpact: the production variant drives the session while the shadow variant produces extraction proposals that are logged but never\nacted on. Comparing shadow proposals against production outcomes gives real-traffic evidence before any user is exposed.\n\nRollout sequence: offline regression suite (fixed set of recorded conversations replayed against the new prompt/model and scored)\n→ shadow mode on live traffic → small A/B percentage → ramp. Note that the conversational and extraction prompts share one API\ncall, so they are versioned and tested as a pair.\n\n\nKEY PRINCIPLE: LLM proposes, Orchestrator decides.\nLLM = conversation, explanation, extraction proposals.\nOrchestrator = state machine, validation, audit log, case linking.",
      "fontSize": 28,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "Model and Prompt Versioning, A/B Testing\nPrompts and model choice are config, not code. A prompt registry holds prompt_id, version, template, and model_id. Every session records which prompt versions and model it ran with, so any quality shift can be attributed.\n\nVariant assignment happens at session start: deterministic hash of user_id into a bucket, variant stamped on the session row. Never switch model or prompt mid-session — assignment is sticky for the whole conversation.\n\nComparison uses the metrics already defined in Evaluation and Monitoring, split per variant: extraction acceptance rate (proposals passing schema validation), re-ask rate per requirement, session completion vs abandonment, time-to-case-creation, plus sampled offline-judge quality scores. Guardrail metrics protect against misleading wins — e.g. a variant with higher completion but double the schema-rejection rate is not an improvement.\n\nBecause the LLM only proposes and the orchestrator decides, candidates can run in shadow mode on real traffic with zero user impact: the production variant drives the session while the shadow variant produces extraction proposals that are logged but never acted on. Comparing shadow proposals against production outcomes gives real-traffic evidence before any user is exposed.\n\nRollout sequence: offline regression suite (fixed set of recorded conversations replayed against the new prompt/model and scored) → shadow mode on live traffic → small A/B percentage → ramp. Note that the conversational and extraction prompts share one API call, so they are versioned and tested as a pair.\n\n\nKEY PRINCIPLE: LLM proposes, Orchestrator decides.\nLLM = conversation, explanation, extraction proposals.\nOrchestrator = state machine, validation, audit log, case linking.",
      "autoResize": false,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    }
